<head>
    <title>
        Honeybees
    </title>
</head>
     <h1>Honeybees are vital social insects living in complex colonies with a queen, female workers, and male drones, renowned
    for producing honey and wax while serving as crucial pollinators for a third of the world's food crops by transferring
    pollen between plants. Workers perform all colony tasks, from foraging nectar and pollen to building hexagonal wax combs
    and defending the hive, using pheromones for communication and clustering together for warmth in winter, highlighting
    their essential role in both agriculture and natural ecosystems.
    Social Structure: Colonies feature one queen (egg-layer), numerous female workers (foragers, builders, cleaners), and
    male drones (mating).
    Pollination Power: They are responsible for pollinating many fruits, vegetables, and nuts, making them essential for
    food security.
    Products: Besides honey, they produce beeswax, royal jelly, and propolis, used in medicine and cosmetics.
    Communication: Bees use pheromones and "waggle dances" to communicate hive needs and food sources.
    Survival: They form tight clusters in winter, vibrating wings to generate heat to keep the queen and brood warm.
</html>